12 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
13 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
14 Article – Education
15 24–703.
16 (a) There is a Maryland Longitudinal Data System Center.
17 (f) The Center shall perform the following functions and duties:
18 (1) Serve as a central repository of student data and workforce data in the
19 Maryland Longitudinal Data System, including data sets provided by:
20 (i) The State Department of Education;
21 (ii) Local education agencies;
22 (iii) The Maryland Higher Education Commission;
23 (iv) Institutions of higher education;
24 (v) The Maryland Department of Labor;
25 (vi) The Department of Juvenile Services; and
26 (vii) The Social Services Administration within the Department of
27 Human Services;
28 (2) Oversee and maintain the warehouse of the Maryland Longitudinal
29 Data System data sets;

HOUSE BILL 293 3
1 (3) Ensure routine and ongoing compliance with the federal Family
2 Educational Rights and Privacy Act and other relevant privacy laws and policies, including:
3 (i) The required use of de–identified data in data research and
4 reporting;
5 (ii) The required disposition of information that is no longer needed;
6 (iii) Providing data security, including the capacity for audit trails;
7 (iv) Providing for performance of regular audits for compliance with
8 data privacy and security standards; and
9 (v) Implementing guidelines and policies that prevent the reporting
10 of other potentially identifying data;
11 (4) Conduct research using timely and accurate student data and
12 workforce data to improve the State’s education system and guide decision making by State
13 and local governments, educational agencies, institutions, teachers, and other education
14 professionals;
15 (5) Conduct research relating to:
16 (i) The impact of State and federal education programs;
17 (ii) The performance of educator preparation programs;
18 (iii) Best practices regarding classroom instruction, education
19 programs and curriculum, and segment alignment; and
20 (iv) The impact child welfare programs have on the educational and
21 economic outcomes of students;
22 (6) At the direction of the Accountability and Implementation Board
23 established in Title 5, Subtitle 4 of this article provide:
24 (i) A researcher designated by the Board access to the data in the
25 Maryland Longitudinal Data System in accordance with the procedures for staff
26 authorization and data access established by the Maryland Longitudinal Data System
27 governing board;
28 (ii) Aggregate data tables; or
29 (iii) Research or evaluation;

4 HOUSE BILL 293
1 (7) Analyze social determinants from the following State agencies and
2 appropriate local agencies that impact the education performance of students and indicate
3 the need for wraparound services of students:
4 (i) The Maryland Department of Health;
5 (ii) The Department of Juvenile Services; and
6 (iii) The Department of Human Services;
7 (8) To the extent practicable, conduct longitudinal studies of the items
8 under this section to evaluate the impact of the Blueprint for Maryland’s Future on the
9 State;
10 (9) SHARE DATA WITH THIRD–PARTY DATA CENTERS ONLY IN
11 ACCORDANCE WITH § 24–703.4 OF THIS SUBTITLE;
12 [(9)] (10) Fulfill information and data requests to facilitate State and
13 federal education reporting with existing State agencies as appropriate; and
14 [(10)] (11) Fulfill approved public information requests.
15 24–703.2.
16 [(e) The Governing Board may authorize the Center to send student information
17 to the United States Census Bureau.]
18 24–703.4.
19 (A) (1) IN THIS SECTION THE FOLLOWING WORDS HAVE THE MEANINGS
20 INDICATED.
21 (2) “FEDRAMP” MEANS THE FEDERAL RISK AND AUTHORIZATION
22 MANAGEMENT PROGRAM MANAGED BY THE U.S. GENERAL SERVICES
23 ADMINISTRATION.
24 (3) “THIRD–PARTY DATA CENTER” MEANS A SECURE
25 COMPUTATIONAL RESEARCH PLATFORM MANAGED BY A PERSON OTHER THAN A
26 STATE AGENCY THAT ALLOWS STATES TO SECURELY SHARE DATA FOR PURPOSES OF
27 DATA MATCHING AND MULTISTATE REPORTING.
28 (B) (1) SUBJECT TO THE REQUIREMENTS OF THIS SECTION, THE
29 GOVERNING BOARD MAY AUTHORIZE THE CENTER TO PROVIDE INDIVIDUAL–LEVEL
30 STUDENT DATA AND INDIVIDUAL–LEVEL WORKFORCE DATA TO A THIRD–PARTY

HOUSE BILL 293 5
1 DATA CENTER ONLY FOR THE PURPOSE OF FACILITATING MULTISTATE RESEARCH
2 AND REPORTING ON STUDENT OUTCOMES.
3 (2) THE GOVERNING BOARD MAY AUTHORIZE THE SHARING OF DATA
4 UNDER PARAGRAPH (1) OF THIS SUBSECTION ONLY WITH ONE THIRD–PARTY DATA
5 CENTER AT A TIME.
6 (C) (1) BEFORE AUTHORIZING THE CENTER TO PROVIDE DATA TO A
7 THIRD–PARTY DATA CENTER, THE GOVERNING BOARD SHALL ENSURE THAT THE
8 THIRD–PARTY DATA CENTER:
9 (I) HAS DATA HANDLING AND SECURITY STANDARDS THAT ARE
10 AT LEAST AS RIGOROUS AS THOSE EMPLOYED BY THE CENTER;
11 (II) IS A FEDRAMP–AUTHORIZED AND –CERTIFIED PLATFORM;
12 (III) USES PERSONALLY IDENTIFIABLE INFORMATION ONLY TO
13 THE EXTENT THAT IS NECESSARY FOR MATCHING STUDENT DATA AND WORKFORCE
14 DATA WITH DATA FROM OTHER STATES;
15 (IV) EMPLOYS PRIVACY–ENHANCING TECHNIQUES, INCLUDING
16 DATA HASHING, IN PLACE OF PERSONALLY IDENTIFIABLE DATA WHENEVER
17 APPROPRIATE;
18 (V) USES ONLY DE–IDENTIFIED DATA FOR ANALYTIC
19 PURPOSES;
20 (VI) RELEASES ONLY AGGREGATE DATA IN REPORTS AND OTHER
21 OUTPUT; AND
22 (VII) DOES NOT REPORT DATA IN ANY FORM THAT MAY BE USED
23 TO IDENTIFY INDIVIDUALS BASED ON THE SIZE OR UNIQUENESS OF THE
24 POPULATION UNDER CONSIDERATION.
25 (2) BEFORE PROVIDING ANY DATA TO A THIRD–PARTY DATA CENTER,
26 THE CENTER SHALL ENTER INTO A WRITTEN DATA SHARING AGREEMENT WITH A
27 THIRD–PARTY DATA CENTER, IN WHICH THE THIRD–PARTY DATA CENTER AGREES
28 TO COMPLY WITH:
29 (I) THE CONDITIONS LISTED UNDER PARAGRAPH (1) OF THIS
30 SUBSECTION;

6 HOUSE BILL 293
1 (II) STATE AND FEDERAL LAWS RELATING TO DATA PRIVACY;
2 AND
3 (III) ANY OTHER CRITERIA THE GOVERNING BOARD
4 DETERMINES ARE APPROPRIATE.
5 (3) EACH YEAR, THE GOVERNING BOARD SHALL REVIEW EACH AN
6 AUTHORIZED DATA SHARING AGREEMENT TO ENSURE THAT THE USE OF STUDENT
7 DATA AND WORKFORCE DATA BY THE THIRD–PARTY DATA CENTER REMAINS
8 COMPLIANT WITH THE TERMS OF THE AGREEMENT.
9 (D) BEFORE PROVIDING ANY DATA TO A THIRD–PARTY DATA CENTER, THE
10 GOVERNING BOARD SHALL AFFIRMATIVELY APPROVE:
11 (1) THE SHARING OF THE DATA ELEMENTS THAT CONSTITUTE EACH
12 DATA SET;
13 (2) THE SHARING OF EACH DATA SET; AND
14 (3) EACH PROPOSED RESEARCH OR REPORTING PROJECT THAT
15 SEEKS TO USE MARYLAND DATA.
16 (E) (1) WITHIN 30 DAYS AFTER ENTERING INTO A WRITTEN DATA
17 SHARING AGREEMENT WITH A THIRD–PARTY DATA CENTER IN ACCORDANCE WITH
18 THIS SECTION, THE CENTER SHALL SUBMIT A REPORT TO THE SENATE COMMITTEE
19 ON EDUCATION, ENERGY, AND THE ENVIRONMENT AND THE HOUSE WAYS AND
20 MEANS COMMITTEE, IN ACCORDANCE WITH § 2–1257 OF THE STATE GOVERNMENT
21 ARTICLE, THAT INCLUDES:
22 (I) THE NAME OF THE THIRD–PARTY DATA CENTER;
23 (II) A SUMMARY OF THE DATA TO BE SHARED; AND
24 (III) THE PURPOSE OF AND VALUE TO THE STATE FOR ENTERING
25 INTO THE DATA SHARING AGREEMENT.
26 (2) WITHIN 1 YEAR OF THE DATE THE REPORT UNDER PARAGRAPH (1)
27 OF THIS SUBSECTION WAS SUBMITTED AND EACH YEAR THEREAFTER UNTIL THE
28 DATA SHARING AGREEMENT IS NO LONGER IN EFFECT, THE CENTER SHALL SUBMIT
29 A REPORT TO THE SENATE COMMITTEE ON EDUCATION, ENERGY, AND THE
30 ENVIRONMENT AND THE HOUSE WAYS AND MEANS COMMITTEE, IN ACCORDANCE
31 WITH § 2–1257 OF THE STATE GOVERNMENT ARTICLE, THAT DESCRIBES:
32 (I) THE STATUS OF THE DATA SHARING AGREEMENT;

HOUSE BILL 293 7
1 (II) HOW THE DATA IS BEING USED TO FURTHER THE PURPOSES
2 AND STATED VALUE OF THE DATA SHARING AGREEMENT; AND
3 (III) ANY VIOLATIONS OF THE DATA SHARING AGREEMENT, IF
4 ANY, AND STEPS TAKEN TO REMEDY THE VIOLATIONS.
5 24–704.
6 (a) There is a Governing Board of the Center.
7 (g) The Governing Board shall:
8 (1) Establish the organizational placement and location of the Center after
9 seeking and evaluating proposals from interested entities based on criteria that shall
10 include:
11 (i) The ability of the entity to support the operation of a large data
12 system;
13 (ii) Strength of funding support; and
14 (iii) Expertise in data security;
15 (2) Develop an implementation plan to phase in the establishment and
16 operation of the Maryland Longitudinal Data System and the Center;
17 (3) Provide general oversight and direction to the Center;
18 (4) Approve the annual budget for the Center;
19 (5) Establish the policy and research agenda of the Center;
20 (6) Before the incorporation of any individual data in the Maryland
21 Longitudinal Data System:
22 (i) Create an inventory of the individual student data:
23 1. Proposed to be maintained in the system; and
24 2. Required to be reported by State and federal education
25 mandates;
26 (ii) Develop and implement policies to comply with the federal
27 Family Educational Rights and Privacy Act and any other privacy measures, as required
28 by law or the Governing Board; and

8 HOUSE BILL 293
1 (iii) Develop a detailed data security and safeguarding plan that
2 includes:
3 1. Authorized access and authentication for authorized
4 access;
5 2. Privacy compliance standards;
6 3. Privacy and security audits;
7 4. Breach notification and procedures; and
8 5. Data retention and disposition policies;
9 (7) APPROVE DATA SHARING WITH THIRD–PARTY DATA CENTERS IN
10 ACCORDANCE WITH § 24–703.4 OF THIS SUBTITLE;
11 [(7)] (8) Oversee routine and ongoing compliance with the federal Family
12 Educational Rights and Privacy Act and other relevant privacy laws and policies;
13 [(8)] (9) Ensure that any contracts that govern databases that are
14 outsourced to private vendors include express provisions that safeguard privacy and
15 security and include penalties for noncompliance;
16 [(9)] (10) Designate a standard and compliance timeline for electronic
17 transcripts that includes the use of SASID to ensure the uniform and efficient transfer of
18 student data between local education agencies and institutions of higher education; and
19 [(10)] (11) Review research requirements and set policies for the approval
20 of data requests from State and local agencies, the Maryland General Assembly, and the
21 public.
22 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect July
23 1, 2026.
Approved:
